[SN]TITLE[SN]
US stocks rise after rebounds in Asia and Europe

[SN]FIRST-SENTENCE[SN]
(Close): US stocks ended the day higher on Thursday after rebounds in European and Asian markets.

[SN]RESTBODY[SN]
There were no further signs of the technical problems which had hit trading on Wall Street for almost four hours on Wednesday.
The Dow Jones gained 0.19% higher, up 33.2 points to 17,548.62, while the S&P 500 was also ahead, by 0.23%, or 4.63 points, at 2,051.31.
And the tech-heavy Nasdaq was up 0.26%, or 12.64 points, at 4,922.40.
Earlier in the day, mainland Chinese shares had rebounded after regulators took further steps to try to calm the stock market.
The Shanghai Composite index reversed earlier losses to close up 5.76%, its biggest percentage gain since 2009.
Meanwhile, the Federal Reserve's June meeting minutes showed that an interest rate hike might be pushed back, with officials saying they needed to see more signs of a strengthening domestic economy before raising rates.
Winners on the Dow included Travelers Company, Pfizer and JP Morgan Chase, which all added more than 1%.
The biggest fallers were Intel and Caterpillar, which shed 1.9% and 0.7% respectively.
